<TEXT>
a jury has been picked and sent home for the 
weekend pending opening arguments monday in the trial of suspected 
hijacker fawaz younis 
the case tests a 1984 law giving the united states jurisdiction 
in incidents involving american hostages abroad 
us district judge aubrey robinson jr asked prospective jurors 
whether they had ever been victims of air piracy or had any links 
with the middle east 
about half the 57 prospective jurors stood up when asked whether 
any had heard of the case in which younis allegedly led a band of 
armed men that seized a royal jordanian airliner in beirut in june 
1985 no one was killed in the hijacking 
the jury plus four women alternates went home for the weekend 
under strict instructions from robinson to discuss the case with no 
one including your preacher and to avoid media coverage of the 
trial 
in september 1987 younis was arrested by federal agents who 
lured him to a twomasted sailing yacht off the coast of cyprus in 
the mediterranean sea with the promise of a drug deal and a party 
according to pretrial evidence and documents 
younis was transferred successively to a navy ammunition ship 
the uss butte and a carrier the uss saratoga then flown nonstop 
to andrews air force base near washington 
the statute under which younis is being tried was passed in 1984 
to give the united states jurisdiction in cases involving american 
hostages abroad domestic hostagetakers have been convicted under 
the statute but no one besides younis has been charged with an 
overseas hijacking and prosecuted under it 
the chief prosecutor assistant us attorney ramsey johnson 
told the court he planned to call as witnesses six fbi agents two 
navy doctors and four passengers from the jetliner 
defense attorney francis d carter said he would call as 
witnesses two federal agents and helena cobban a scholar on the 
middle east he indicated during a pretrial hearing wednesday he 
will call younis to the stand 
younis 29 a shiite moslem from lebanon faces life imprisonment 
if convicted 
bearded with brown hair and brown eyes younis appeared in the 
courtroom wearing a light gray sweater and a tie throughout the 
proceedings he smiled and joked with an arablanguage translator 
supplied by the court 
the defense counsel said at a pretrial hearing he would argue 
that his client seized control of the airplane under orders from the 
amal militia to which he belonged the amal is a shiite moslem 
faction in lebanon 
evidence against younis includes a videotape of him on the tarmac 
at beirut airport announcing that the boeing 727 aircraft would be 
blown up no one was killed in the 39hour ordeal which ended when 
the airplane was destroyed after being evacuated 
during the trial expected to last at least two weeks federal 
officials will be seeking to limit disclosure of details of the 
elaborate clandestine operation in which younis was captured 
</TEXT>
