<TEXT>
the united air lines 747 that lost nine 
passengers when a cargo door and section of fuselage blew away over 
the pacific ocean was one of a group of older boeing jets under 
order to modify the lock system on their cargo doors 
failure of the door was one of several possibilities 
investigators were exploring today as cause for the gaping hole in 
united flight 811 when it returned to honolulu after taking off on a 
flight to auckland new zealand 
other possibilities included structural failure an engine 
problem that sent parts flying into the fuselage or a bomb 
a july 1 1988 airworthiness directive from the federal 
aviation administration gave airlines with 156 of the early jumbo 
jets from 30 to 90 days to conduct inspections and any necessary 
repairs depending on the type of door lock they have they were 
also given from 18 to 24 months to make modifications to improve the 
door lock system 
united public relations officials did not return a call late 
friday to inquire whether the damaged airliners cargo doors had 
been inspected or whether the ordered alteration had been made on 
that or other united 747s the airline would have had at least 
another 10 months to make the improvement 
united spokesman lawrence nagin said earlier the airliner had a 
routine maintenance history 
the 18yearold plane is the oldest 747 in uniteds jumbo jet 
fleet and the 89th 747 built by boeing which has produced 712 of 
the aircraft in various versions since 1969 
a boeing spokesman randy harrison said the united plane had 
57793 flying hours and 14849 takeoffs and landings that involved 
pressurizing the cabin we dont consider those high numbers he 
said 
a 14member national transportation safety board team was 
conducting investigation into the cause with assistance from the 
faa united boeing and the fbi 
the july faa directive was prompted by a lower lobe forward 
cargo door with damaged lock sectors that partially opened in 
flight a summary of the directive said 
this condition if not corrected could result in the opening 
of a lower lobe cargo door in flight which could result in rapid 
depressurization of the airplane it said 
faa spokesman mitch barker in seattle said he didnt have the 
technical expertise to say whether a cargo door opening in flight 
could cause a hole to be ripped in the planes fuselage 
the cargo door incident that brought the order was on a pan 
american flight in march 1987 said paul turk of avmark an aviation 
appraisal firm that keeps track of airliners throughout the world 
turk said after examining photographs and videotape of the 
airliner he would expect to see scorch marks on the fuselage and 
luggage if a bomb had gone off and there were none visible in the 
photographs but he said it would take careful inspection to 
determine the cause 
chris witkowski of the aviation consumer action project which 
represents airline passengers said if it is a cargo door problem 
it is a bad omen for safety in the industry because it raises a 
maintenance problem the airline industry dealt with after a fatal 
crash near paris in 1974 
that crash killed more than 350 people aboard a turkish air dc10 
and was the worlds worst air disaster up to the time it occurred 
the cargo door popped off in flight depressurizing the aircraft 
buckling the airliner floor and breaking wires and cables needed to 
control the plane 
boeing spokesman harrison said the structure of boeing aircraft 
is triple redundant safe and because of its design that the 
united plane was able to return to honolulu despite the gaping hole 
in its side 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

