<TEXT>
phone companies must use different prefixes 
for calling services with sexually explicit material supply them 
only by subscription and allow businesses to block those calls a 
state agency ruled 
fridays action by the california public utilities commission was 
hailed as a major ruling by attorney robert gnaizda of public 
advocates who represented 12 groups that sought changes to protect 
consumers and prevent children from running up bills of thousands 
of dollars with the calls 
the tentative decision scheduled to come up for a final vote on 
march 22 expands a 1987 ruling that allowed residential customers 
to block the calls which typically carry 976 prefixes 
businesses and schools have sought the option because many of 
their phones are easily accessible and often go unmonitored 
recorded and live messages intended only for adults would be 
limited to a separate telephone prefix 
in addition to restricting the services to subscription only the 
commission limited costs to no more than 5 for the first minute and 
1 for each additional minute with a 20 maximum cost per call 
gnaizda said the change in perminute charges was the most 
innovative aspect of the commissions ruling 
the largest monthly bill for 976 service known to gnaizda was 
6000 
many of them bills were in the 5000 to 6000 range so 
thats not surprising at all he said 
but gnaizda was skeptical about the plan to have phone companies 
use three different prefixes to differentiate between services with 
sexually explicit material that would be harmful to children and 
provide such messages only by subscription 
theyll never be able to define it he said 
the commission also said pacific bell must contact customers as 
soon as the calls reach 150 or more in a billing period or 
temporarily block those services until the customer has been 
notified and given the chance to stop it 
it also said the seller of the phone service must provide an 
introductory message warning callers of the calls price and giving 
them a chance to hang up without charge 
while this revised settlement does not constitute a perfect 
900 service in our judgment it will produce a service with 
substantial benefit for california the commission said in a 
statement 
our goal is to disconnect dialaporn said pacific bell 
spokesman jim herold but until we have legal authority to do 
that weve designed our new 900 service to solve the problems some 
consumers have had with 976 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

