<TEXT>
president bush flew to china today clasped hands 
with ordinary people in beijings main square and urged chinese 
leaders to join the united states in planting trees of world peace 
so future generations can sit together in the shade 
the president and his wife barbara were jubilant on their 
return to the country where bush served as americas diplomatic 
representative in the mid1970s its great to be back he 
declared 
at a welcoming banquet in the great hall of the people bush 
toasted his host president yang shangkun and recalled a chinese 
proverb that says one generation plants a tree the next sits in 
its shade 
we owe it to mankind to work together for peace and 
international stability bush said let us continue then to 
work together to plant trees together so that the next generation 
ours and yours can sit together in the shade 
in response yang praised bush for making great contributions 
to developing chineseus relations he said that steady 
development of these relations will be of enormous significance 
thousands of people crowded along the wide flagdraped boulevard 
in front of tiananmen square where bush hopped from his limousine 
to shake some hands it was his fifth visit to china since he spent 
two years as the chief us envoy to beijing before formal 
sinoamerican relations were restored 
welcome back someone called out to bush in english the 
president replied in tentative chinese xie xie thank you 
from the airport where he arrived in late afternoon from tokyo 
bush was driven to the diaoyutai state guest house for a formal 
welcome over tea with premier li peng 
the president gave li a pair of texas boots and the premier gave 
bush and his wife barbara a couple of bicycles when he lived here 
previously bush was known for his habit of biking around the 
capital 
en route mrs bush told reporters she was excited to be 
returning to china 
seeing the country for the first time was like seeing a black 
and white movie she said last time we were there three or 
four years ago it was really an emerged nation i love china i 
had very very happy years there 
at tiananmen square where us and chinese flags flew side by 
side chinese people halted their bicycles for a curious glimpse at 
their american guest a few of them applauded 
the bushes visit here blends sentiment and statecraft before 
leaving tokyo the president declared that his talks with 20 foreign 
leaders in the japanese capital had yielded a shared sense of 
satisfaction with the course of eastwest relations and laid a 
good foundation for advancing the security interests of the united 
states and its allies 
bush arrived at beijings old airport now used only by 
highranking chinese officials and visiting dignitaries bush 
wearing an overcoat in 40degree weather waved once as he descended 
the ramp he was followed by his wife who wore a purple coat 
in keeping with chinese custom there was no arrival ceremony or 
statements bush was greeted by vice premier wu xuequian and vice 
foreign minister zhu qizhen and two children gave the president and 
his wife bouquets of flowers 
i know i will marvel at the changes in china since he served 
as head of the us liaison office in 197475 bush told reporters 
earlier he said we obviously have differences but that his 
visit would strength an alreadysolid relationship 
im excited about it theres an openness in china that i never 
would have predicted 15 years ago he said 
his beijing talks were to focus on sinoamerican ties with 
glancing attention to an overflow cup of topics that could spark 
debate including reunifying taiwan with the mainland human rights 
in tibet and trade issues 
