<TEXT>
a world health organization official agrees with 
soviet conclusions that an unsterile syringe infected more than two 
dozen children with the aids virus tass said saturday 
david heimann chief of the who epidemiological department came 
to the soviet union to help medical authorities track the source of 
the virus discovered in 29 infants and six mothers in elista a city 
near the caspian sea 
largescale epidemiological studies helped find the cause of 
the massive infection of the children an unsterilized syringe used 
for injections at a maternity home said tass the official soviet 
news agency 
the virus itself tass said was most probably brought by a man 
who worked in one of the african countries eight years ago 
not everyone infected with the aids virus contracts the deadly 
disease 
the news agency said heimann received full information and did 
not find any data contradicting the conclusions of the soviet 
national commission which held a probe into the accident 
it was not clear in the tass report how the virus was transmitted 
from the unidentified carrier but earlier newspaper reports said 
nurses at the maternity home had been reusing disposable syringes to 
cover up the sale of unused needles to drug addicts 
the toll of 29 infected infants in elitsa is two more than 
reported in january and authorities are continuing to test hundreds 
of infants who were treated in the hospital 
heimann offered the support of the international community 
saying it would be useful to jointly work out methods of treating 
the infected children and providing psychological support for their 
mothers tass said 
after long denying the existence of acquired immune deficiency 
syndrome in the soviet union officials acknowledged about three 
years ago that soviets have been infected and began a campaign 
against the disease 
since 1987 it has been a crime in the soviet union to infect 
anyone with the aids virus and officials are investigating bringing 
charges against medical personnel in the elitsa case since the 
presence of aids was acknowledged in the soviet union officials 
have reported that two people have died of the disease 
acquired immune deficiency syndrome is caused by a virus that 
damages the bodys immune system leaving victims susceptible to 
infections and cancer 
it is spread most often through sexual contact needles or 
syringes shared by drug abusers infected blood or blood products 
and from pregnant women to their offspring 
the scientific name for the virus is human immunodeficiency 
virus or hiv 
</TEXT>
