<TEXT>
here are some of the recent incidents involving 
airliner aging and metal fatigue prior to damage that killed nine 
people friday when an 18yearold united air lines 747 tore open 
over the pacific cause of the incident had not been determined 
january 20 1989 a piedmont airlines 737s dropped an engine 
shortly after takeoff from chicago none of 3 passengers and crew 
was injured and the plane landed safely the aircraft was only seven 
years old but authorities blamed metal fatigue and a cracked bolt 
december 26 1988 an late 1960s eastern airlines boeing 727 
with 104 passengers and six crew aboard was forced to land at yeager 
airport in charleston wva after a 14inch hole opened in its 
fuselage at 31000 feet there were no injuries the incident led to 
fleetwide inspection and discovery of a 3inch crack in another old 
eastern 727 
sept 21 1988 an american airlines 727 made a belly landing at 
dallasfort worth after metal fatigue in its landing gear prevented 
the pilot from opening the wheel well door the 88 passengers and 
crew evacuated with three people injured boeing had recommended 
inspections eight days earlier after finding metal fatigue in the 
same area in other 727s 
may 9 1988 a 20yearold american airlines 727 was forced to 
make an unscheduled landing at detroit after a 15inch crack in a 
wheel well caused a drop in cabin pressure none of the 112 aboard 
was injured 
april 28 1988 a flight attendant was killed and 61 persons 
injured when a portion of the fuselage on a heavily flown aloha 
airlines 737 built in the late 1960s peeled off at 24000 feet 
during an aloha flight from hilo to honolulu tiny cracks were found 
later in nearly half the aging boeing 737 jetliners inspected in the 
months following and the faa ordered the reriveting of hundreds of 
older 737s 
dec 5 1987 an engine fell of a usair 737 in philadelphia 
causing no injuries the faa ordered inspection of enginemount 
bolts on some 737s 
</TEXT>
