prime minister charles haughey on saturday 
renewed his call for talks with northern irelands protestant 
leaders but reaffirmed the governments commitment to the 
angloirish accord they oppose 
haughey whose earlier appeals for discussions with northern 
ireland have been rejected by protestant leaders said he believed 
that such talks would be a step toward peace in northern ireland 
sectarian violence between roman catholics and protestants in the 
british province has cost 2722 lives in the past 20 years 93 of 
them in 1988 and 11 this year 
speaking at the annual conference of his fianna fail party in 
dublin haughey said i believe the political circumstances are 
opportune at present for such a meeting 
the dialogue that i have in mind need not involve any 
commitments he said nothing need be prejudged nothing ruled 
out 
this would be the clearest possible signal to all that there 
was some possibility however tenuous of progress out of the 
present horror if such a development could bring us even one step 
forward one step away from violence as i sincerely believe it 
would then it is difficult to see how the unionist leadership can 
be morally justified in refusing the invitation i now again extend 
to them 
haughey made it clear there was no prospect of scrapping the 
angloirish agreement that gives the largely catholic republic a say 
in the affairs of the predominantly protestant province 
rejection of the accord is the main condition set by the hardline 
protestants for any dialogue 
in a reference to the continuing tension with britain over 
extradition of suspected terrorists haughey underlined offical 
determination to ensure that the rights of irish citizens wanted 
abroad for any offense would be fully safeguarded 
