<TEXT>
the united nations will send a small 
avalanche of food to thousands of starving sudanese before rains 
cut off supply routes the director of unicef said saturday 
millions of people are at risk in sudan which is ravaged by 
civil war drought and crop failures james p grant the head of 
the un childrens fund told the associated press 
one could certainly say that over 100000 people will live or 
die it depends on getting supplies prepositioned in southern and 
central sudan before the rains come and even planes are grounded 
in may through november grant said 
its really an unprecedented effort on this scale to be done 
in such a short time frame under such difficult conditions he 
said 
grant and other un relief officials met at un headquarters 
saturday where they decided an airlift of 80000 tons of food was 
required to fend off mass starvation among 4 million sudanese 
we have some very hopeful auguries of increasing the modest 
stocks of supplies into a small avalanche said grant 
on march 89 grant will lead a relief planning meeting of un 
and private aid agencies in khartoum at the invitation of sudans 
government 
no figure was available for the cost of the airlift and other 
elements of the relief campaign but in november the cost of meeting 
the most urgent needs was estimated at 722 million grant said 
relief operations in sudan have been crippled by the civil war 
between the predominantly moslem government in the north and a 
rebellion in the christian and animist south by the sudan peoples 
liberation army 
both the government and the rebels have sometimes blocked 
supplies from reaching areas held by the other side 
last week sudans military forces told prime minister sadek mahdi 
to reform his government and seek peace with the rebels or resign 
if there was an agreement on a ceasefire and talks between the 
parties this would clearly ease the situation grant said but he 
said government upheaval could hinder the delivery of aid 
